1.	Node uses the CommonJS module system, while in the browser we are starting to see the ES Modules standard being implemented.
2.	In the browser, we don’t have all the nice APIs that Node.js provides through its modules, like the filesystem access functionality.
3.	Need Babel to transform your code to be ES5-compatible before shipping it to the browser, but in Node, you won’t need that.
4.	frontend developer who extensively uses Javascript, Node apps brings with it, a huge advantage - the comfort of programming everything, the frontend and the backend, in a single language.
5.	In the browser, most of the time what you are doing is interacting with the DOM, or other Web Platform APIs like Cookies. Those do not exist in Node, of course. You don’t have the document, window and all the other objects that are provided by the browser.
